---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import GoDeeperDoor from '../components/GoDeeperDoor.astro';
import CollapseRadiate from '../components/CollapseRadiate.tsx';
import WhoDoesWhat from '../components/WhoDoesWhat.tsx';
import FormatSwitcher from '../components/FormatSwitcher.tsx';
import ClusterTabs from '../components/ClusterTabs.tsx';
import TwoAgents from '../components/TwoAgents.tsx';
import '../styles/l0.css';
---
<BaseLayout title="The Knowledge Atom" layer="L0">

  <!-- ACT 1 — THE LEVERAGE -->
  <header class="hero on-ink" id="a1">
    <div class="grid-bg"></div>
    <div class="wrap hero-grid">
      <div>
        <div class="eyebrow">Act 01 — The Leverage</div>
        <h1>We own roughly <em>10,000 courses.</em> Half have never been opened.</h1>
        <p class="sub">A library that large isn't an asset — it's a liability that decays quietly. Every course is a sealed box: knowledge trapped inside one format, impossible to reuse, expensive to update, invisible to the people who need an answer right now.</p>
        <div class="stat">
          <div class="n">~1 in 10</div>
          <div class="t">hours of corporate training ever changes what someone actually does on the job.</div>
          <div class="src mono">— Training-transfer research (Baldwin &amp; Ford)</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <CollapseRadiate client:visible />
        <p class="stage-label">ONE 30-MIN COURSE → ONE ATOM → MANY FORMS</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- ACT 2 — THE ATOM -->
  <section class="act" id="a2">
    <div class="grid-bg"></div>
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="act-no mono">Act 02 — The Atom</div>
      <h2 class="head">The atom <em style="font-style:italic;font-family:var(--serif)">is</em> the knowledge — not a box that holds it.</h2>
      <p class="lede">We break that 30-minute course into its smallest teachable truths. Each becomes an atom: one verified idea, written once as canonical text. Every video, quiz, and job aid is a <em style="font-style:italic">view</em> derived from it — so when the truth changes, every view updates from one place.</p>

      <div class="split">
        <!-- Specimen card -->
        <aside class="specimen">
          <div class="tag">Specimen · atm_0191</div>
          <h3>Severity Classification for Tier-1 Escalation</h3>
          <div class="meta mono">
            <span>ver <b>v4</b></span>
            <span>status <b>Verified</b></span>
            <span>hash <b>9f2a·c41e</b></span>
            <span>skill <b>Apply</b></span>
          </div>
          <div class="ktext">
            <span class="lbl">knowledge_text · canonical</span>
            Escalation severity is set by what a fix <b>requires</b> — authority, system access, or expertise the rep doesn't hold — not by how upset the caller is. Active harm (an unauthorized transfer draining funds) escalates now; a single disputed charge inside the window is handled at Tier&nbsp;1. Emotion is a service cue, not a severity signal.
          </div>
        </aside>

        <!-- Cluster tabs (React island) -->
        <div class="clusters">
          <ClusterTabs client:visible />
          <GoDeeperDoor href="/anatomy" layer="L1" label="Explore all 19 fields in the Anatomy" />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ACT 3 — THE DUET -->
  <section class="act act-3" id="a3">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="act-no mono">Act 03 — The Duet</div>
      <h2 class="head">An agent does the production. A person does the judgment.</h2>
      <p class="lede">This isn't automation replacing instructional designers — it's augmentation. The builder agent drafts, decomposes, and derives at machine speed. The human contributes the part no model can: what's actually true, what edge cases matter, and what behavior we're trying to change.</p>

      <WhoDoesWhat client:visible />

      <div class="augment-stat">
        <div class="n">~3×</div>
        <div class="t">improvement in knowledge-work output when humans and AI systems collaborate vs. either working alone.</div>
        <div class="src mono">— Brynjolfsson, Rock &amp; Syverson (MIT)</div>
      </div>

      <div class="act3-bridge">
        <p class="act3-bridge-text">Want to see the full sequence — the exact handoffs between agent and human, step by step, for one real atom?</p>
        <GoDeeperDoor href="/how-atoms-are-made" layer="L3" label="See exactly how atoms are made" />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ACT 4 — SCALE -->
  <section class="act" id="a4">
    <div class="grid-bg"></div>
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="act-no mono">Act 04 — The Multiplication</div>
      <h2 class="head">One atom. Every format a learner needs. <em style="font-style:italic;font-family:var(--serif)">Same</em> source of truth.</h2>
      <p class="lede">Here is the leverage made literal. Pick a format — the agent re-expresses atm_0191's single knowledge_text into that form on demand. Notice the hash never changes. Update the atom once, and every form below updates with it.</p>

      <FormatSwitcher client:visible mode="static" />

      <GoDeeperDoor href="/example" layer="L2" label="Walk through a full atom example" />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ACT 5 — TWO AGENTS -->
  <section class="act act-5 on-ink" id="a5">
    <div class="grid-bg"></div>
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="act-no mono">Act 05 — The Agents</div>
      <h2 class="head">Two agents. <em style="font-style:italic;font-family:var(--serif)">One atom.</em></h2>
      <p class="lede">The atom doesn't sit in a library. It powers two live agents: one that answers questions in the flow of work, one that builds skills over time. Neither invents anything. Both read from the same canonical source.</p>

      <TwoAgents client:visible hideChain={true} />

      <GoDeeperDoor href="/the-system" layer="L4" label="From assignment to learned skill →" />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CLOSING CAP -->
  <section class="close-cap on-ink">
    <div class="grid-bg"></div>
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="eyebrow">The bet</div>
      <h2>The course library doesn't scale. <em>Knowledge</em> does.</h2>

      <div class="twostat">
        <div class="item">
          <div class="n"><em>~70%</em> forgotten</div>
          <div class="t">of new learning is gone within a day without reinforcement (Ebbinghaus). Atoms can be re-served as microlearning on a schedule.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="item">
          <div class="n">~9 in 10</div>
          <div class="t">training programs measure only whether learners <em style="font-style:italic;color:var(--paper-txt)">liked</em> it — never whether behavior changed (Kirkpatrick Level 1).</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="kill-list">
        <div class="kill-item">10,000-course catalogs</div>
        <div class="kill-item">SCORM packages</div>
        <div class="kill-item">"AI-generated courses."</div>
      </div>

      <p class="kicker">Build the knowledge once. Let the agent multiply the formats. Keep people exactly where judgment lives.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <footer class="site-footer mono">THE KNOWLEDGE ATOM · WORKING CONCEPT · atm_0191 SHOWN FOR ILLUSTRATION</footer>

</BaseLayout>
